---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Text from "@/components/fundations/elements/Text.astro";
import Wrapper from "@/components/fundations/containers/Wrapper.astro";
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Collective Charter"
  description="The governing charter for the UI Collective, covering purpose, membership, conduct, governance, and dispute resolution."
  pageType="webpage"
>
  <section>
    <Wrapper variant="standard" class="py-12">
      <Text
        tag="h1"
        variant="textBase"
        class="text-foreground font-medium text-balance"
      >
        Collective Charter
      </Text>
      <Wrapper variant="prose" class="mt-2 pt-2 border-t border-border">
        <h2>Preamble</h2>
        <p>
          The UI Collective is a professional group for independent creators who
          build and sell templates, UI kits, component libraries, and design
          systems. We are founders, makers, and full-time operators in this
          space, brought together by a shared belief in quality, honesty, and
          the long-term health of the industry.
        </p>
        <p>
          Membership in the Collective is a public signal that you are a known
          and trusted creator who respects intellectual property, follows
          ethical standards, and works in good faith.
        </p>
        <h2>Article I — Purpose</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Professional Standards.</strong> Establish and uphold shared standards
            of quality, ethics, and professionalism for commercial template and UI
            work.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Industry Integrity.</strong> Identify, discuss, and respond to
            harmful behavior in the industry, including plagiarism, license violations,
            deceptive marketing, and repeated IP theft.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Credible Membership.</strong> Keep membership meaningful, so that
            being part of the Collective stands for professionalism and good standing.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h2>Article II — Membership</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Eligibility</h3>
        <p>Membership is open to individuals and businesses who:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Run an active, full-time business creating and selling templates, UI
            kits, component libraries, or design systems.
          </li>
          <li>Have a public record of shipped commercial products.</li>
          <li>
            Agree to follow this Charter and the Collective&apos;s Code of
            Conduct.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 2 — Admission</h3>
        <p>
          There are no dues or fees to join. To apply, contact any current
          member. Applications are reviewed internally, and decisions are based
          on eligibility, professional track record, and alignment with this
          Charter.
        </p>
        <h3>Section 3 — Good Standing</h3>
        <p>A member is in good standing when they:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Comply with this Charter and the Code of Conduct.</li>
          <li>Take part constructively in Collective discussions and work.</li>
          <li>
            Have no unresolved and substantiated complaints from fellow members
            or the broader community.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 4 — Suspension & Removal</h3>
        <p>A member may be suspended or removed for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Repeated or serious violations of the Code of Conduct.</li>
          <li>
            Substantiated findings of plagiarism, IP theft, or license fraud.
          </li>
          <li>Conduct that brings the Collective into disrepute.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Removal requires a formal review process as defined in Article V.</p>
        <h2>Article III — Code of Conduct</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Ethical Practice</h3>
        <p>Members shall:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Respect the intellectual property of others, including code,
            designs, copy, and visual assets.
          </li>
          <li>
            Comply with all applicable copyright, trademark, and licensing laws.
          </li>
          <li>
            Present their products honestly, with no deceptive screenshots, fake
            reviews, inflated claims, or misleading demos.
          </li>
          <li>
            Honor the licenses they sell and the licenses of the open-source
            tools they build on.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 2 — Good Faith & Professionalism</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            All discussions, especially around disputes or infringement claims,
            should begin from a position of good faith.
          </li>
          <li>
            Present concerns professionally and give others the benefit of the
            doubt.
          </li>
          <li>
            Focus on resolution and constructive outcomes, not public spectacle.
          </li>
          <li>
            Direct, private communication should be the first step before
            escalation.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 3 — Solidarity Against Bad Actors</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The Collective identifies and responds to harmful patterns in the
            industry, including serial copying, license violations, and
            fraudulent behavior.
          </li>
          <li>
            Members support each other in enforcing their rights, including
            coordinated public statements, shared legal resources, and platform
            reporting when warranted.
          </li>
          <li>
            Calling out bad actors is done with evidence, proportionality, and
            professionalism, never as a weapon for competitive advantage.
          </li>
          <li>
            For detailed guidance on evaluating copyright and infringement
            claims, see the{" "}
            <a href="/copyright-guide">Copyright Claims Guide</a>.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Article IV — Governance</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The Collective operates as a flat, consensus-driven group. As
          membership grows, the Collective may elect:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            A <strong>Steward</strong> (or rotating Stewards) responsible for running
            meetings, maintaining records, and managing membership.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Working Groups</strong> for specific initiatives, such as Legal
            Resources or Industry Standards.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 2 — Decision-Making</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Day-to-day decisions are made through open discussion and rough
            consensus.
          </li>
          <li>
            Major decisions, including Charter amendments, member removals, and
            official public statements, require a formal vote with a defined
            quorum and majority threshold.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Section 3 — Meetings</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The Collective meets regularly, with cadence determined by members,
            through virtual calls or async discussion.
          </li>
          <li>This Charter is reviewed annually to keep it relevant.</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Article V — Dispute Resolution</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Between Members</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Private Resolution.</strong> Parties are expected to attempt direct,
            private resolution first.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mediation.</strong> If private resolution fails, either party
            may request mediation by the Steward or a neutral member.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Collective Review.</strong> If mediation fails, the matter may
            be brought before the full membership for review and a binding recommendation.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h3>Section 2 — Against External Parties</h3>
        <p>When a member identifies a bad actor or industry-wide problem:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Documentation.</strong> The member presents evidence to the Collective
            privately.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Assessment.</strong> The Collective reviews the evidence, applying
            the good-faith standard.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Action.</strong> The Collective decides on a proportional response,
            which may range from a private warning to a coordinated public statement,
            platform reporting, or legal referral.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h2>Article VI — Public Representation</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            No individual member speaks on behalf of the Collective without
            authorization.
          </li>
          <li>Official statements are issued only after a formal vote.</li>
          <li>
            Members may reference their membership in the UI Collective as a
            public mark of professional standing.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Article VII — Amendments</h2>
        <p>
          This Charter may be amended by a two-thirds majority vote of all
          members in good standing. Proposed amendments must be circulated at
          least 14 days before a vote.
        </p>
        <h2>Signatures</h2>
        <p>
          By joining the UI Collective, members confirm that they have read,
          understood, and agree to follow this Charter.
        </p>
      </Wrapper>
    </Wrapper>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
